        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The Council of Europe recorded 266 physical attacks, intimidation, arrests, and reprisals against journalists in 2024. This comes from the European Press Freedom Report 2024, which is from 15 press freedom NGOs and journalist associations. The rise of disinformation, including AI-generated content, weakens independent journalism. The Council of Europe raised concerns over growing government control over the media, with Italy and Slovakia struggling.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The report indicates increasing <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-03-2025-h1-1-violence-against-journalists" target="_blank">violence against journalists</a>, especially in Ukraine and Georgia. Approximately 64% of the recorded attacks occurred in Russia and Russian-occupied Ukraine. It shows Georgia as having the sharpest decline in press freedom. Georgia saw a 10% increase in physical attacks and intimidation due to protests over controversial laws and the country’s EU aspirations. 
       </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The European Commission is working on strengthening legal protections for journalists. One method is through the European Media Freedom Act and a directive to counter harmful lawsuits. Germany and the Netherlands were praised for efforts to improve journalist safety.
</p>
