        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">No more intel-sharing </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: The US stopped sharing intelligence information with Ukraine following the suspension of foreign aid.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The US has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-03-2025-h3-3-stopped-sharing-intelligence-with-ukraine" target="_blank">stopped sharing intelligence with Ukraine</a> following Donald Trump's suspension of military aid. This marks a significant setback for Kyiv in its fight against Russia. The suspension affects Ukraine’s ability to carry out effective long-range drone strikes. It lacks crucial information on Russian targets, bomber movements, and missile launches. It is unclear if this also impacts Russian forces in occupied Ukrainian areas.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">US officials indicated that the ban could be lifted if peace talks progress. US envoy Keith Kellogg said the move was intentional to get Ukraine to realize the US was serious about ending the war. Despite last week's heated discussion, President Zelenskyy is willing to negotiate under Trump’s leadership. Many have criticized it as a way to hold Ukraine hostage for its minerals.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Experts argue that Ukraine can still rely on open-source intelligence and human resources to track targets. France has also stepped in and is sharing its intelligence with Ukraine. Russia has escalated its attacks on Ukraine. One of the attacks on Wednesday night hit Zelenskyy's hometown of Kryvyi Rih and killed four people.</p>
        </mj-text>
