            <strong>🇭🇰 Hong Kong court stops Tiananmen activists' conviction</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Hong Kong’s top court has overturned the convictions of three former pro-democracy Hong Kong Alliance members. They were prosecuted for organizing the annual candlelight vigil for the Tiananmen Square crackdown. The Court of Final Appeal ruled that the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-03-2025-br1-4-convictions-were-a-miscarriage-of-justice" target="_blank">convictions were a miscarriage of justice</a>. The court cited key facts that were censored during the trial. They were jailed in 2023 for failing to provide information about the Alliance’s members and finances.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The court criticized the prosecution for not presenting sufficient evidence, especially alleged foreign influence on the group. This rare victory for Hong Kong’s pro-democracy movement follows a wave of repression under China’s national security law. Meanwhile, the Court of Appeal dismissed a separate appeal by activist Tam Tak-chi to overturn his sedition conviction.</p>
        </mj-text>
