          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Why do we celebrate International Women’s Day?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/Women-march-International-Womens-Day.png" alt="Women march on the street on International Women’s Day" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Women march on the street on International Women’s Day. Credits: History Extra</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">International Women's Day (IWD) began in the early 20th century as part of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-07-03-2025-f1-6-broader-movement-for-womens-rights-and-social-justice" target="_blank">broader movement for women’s rights and social justice</a>. The first official National Women's Day was celebrated on February 28, 1909, in the United States. It was organized by the Socialist Party of America to honor the 1908 garment workers' strike in New York. 
</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The following year, the International Socialist Women's Congress in Copenhagen proposed the idea of an International Women's Day. The idea gained traction, and the first IWD was celebrated on March 19, 1911, in several European countries, including Austria, Denmark, Germany, and Switzerland.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Despite originating in the West, International Women's Day took off in the Soviet Union and Warsaw and was more widespread in the non-Western world for many years. The United Nations officially recognized it in 1977 and established March 8 as the permanent date. Many dedicate International Women's Day to promoting gender equality and commemorating women's achievements.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">However, some issues are raised with feminism. One of the main critiques of modern feminism is that it is tailored more towards well-off women's issues in Western countries. Insufficient representation of women's issues outside North America and Europe has led to calls for more women's groups to be more intersectional in addressing women's issues worldwide.</p>
        </mj-text>
